[{"id":27635,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/14d9c468-f21c-42de-9220-a2b609f24fed.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 156px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c7b403d1-ddae-4a9e-aaf5-f70d86a78d4d.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 111px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e6884dcf-f016-4c6b-9661-bcc32ecda062.png\" style=\"width: 249px; height: 240px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/08ee4d77-5310-4c7c-b87a-ef73d15176c8.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 138px;\"/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><strong>Freidel-Crafts Acylation:</strong></p><ul> <li>Friedel-Crafts acylation reaction is a type of reaction where an acyl group is added to an aromatic ring.</li> <li>This reaction occurs in the presence of an acid chloride <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math> and a Lewis acid catalyst like Aluminium chloride <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</li> <li>Friedel-Crafts acylation reaction, changes the aromatic ring into a aromatic ketone.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/de8f3d55-e97a-44e6-8539-3bf23280d899.png\" style=\"width: 704px; height: 521px;\"/></li></ul>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27681,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/71c6330d-31e4-4fdc-8ffa-a9a085be0624-image.png\" style=\"width: 122px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/64e71f11-9d15-486e-a8b5-e0f7fa9c3a5a-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/adbeb9f2-d1b3-409c-9e75-3953380b66b8-image.png\" style=\"width: 121px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/33e701db-30f2-4d96-81de-505b434c4ac0-image.png\" style=\"width: 110px; height: 135px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/448bb025-0c1c-47f1-8abf-c266f31a6e64-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 124px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27665,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow></mrow></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math> is very selective and usually used to reduce acid into alcohol.</p><p>Borane is commonly used for the reduction of carboxylic acids in the presence of esters, lactones, amides, halides and other functional groups. In addition, borane rapidly reduces aldehydes, ketones, and alkenes.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27624,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c_n0EjvFgKMuxdALDlJFAU2HhP58wehMW_XMTXwaDME.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/P7wbZ-bHgm1Ui0BqxGlSgAq4vDkTS6UpQi0ZVOcSyGI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/v4apkzB6hZn1arP9pp-AkvyLpTACuDz5Zi-5ER28AaU.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dub3OcY7XY4044kcOJMKLFUeGnxCdNzHByLN7Zn4Jog.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Concept - Those compounds which are more acidic than $\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3$ can gives effervescence of $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ with aq. $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$.<br />Release $\\mathrm{CO}_2 \\uparrow$ gas with aq. NaHCO 3<br />$\\Rightarrow[\\text { A.S. }]_{\\text {Comp. }} \\gt [\\text { A.S. }]_{\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3}$<br />$\\rightarrow$ Option 1,2 and 3 gives effervescence of $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ gas with $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$<br />$\\rightarrow$ Option (4) Not gives $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ gas with $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27656,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp; group attached with carbonyl bond will decrease reactivity of acid derivative towards hydrolysis. For halogen&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;dominate over&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;therefore, acid chloride is most reactive. As extent of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;effect&nbsp;increases, reactivity decreases. Overall, order of reactivity is:<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/56ba87b0-a548-4ac8-8b12-0d37a5d31f1d-image.png\" style=\"width: 483px; height: 141px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27670,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/025580cc-a238-437f-92b5-943bc721531d-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 129px;\" /></p><br />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4119bec6-944a-4c78-bdad-fc6b091046e2-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/159706ba-fa12-4622-9789-c72c8bb39290-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 112px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/187c93d4-fcc8-40bd-93af-aeff698192fa-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 130px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4c014ab9-cf3a-401a-99f0-dc350a68c76e-image12.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 106px;\" /><br />Alkaline <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></math> oxidise&nbsp;benzylic carbon to the carboxylic acid.</p><p>Alkenes react with acidified potassium permanganate. Potassium Permanganate is a strong oxidant, and will initially convert the double bond to two alcohol (OH) groups.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27653,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9b487b52-6128-48ab-902c-062b8b7e310e-image.png\" style=\"width: 325px; height: 132px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8094e1cf-8b9e-4030-b496-5095b35bc001-image.png\" style=\"width: 325px; height: 132px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9f8312d8-a1bf-42d6-97ee-e8bce0112cc9-image.png\" style=\"width: 308px; height: 132px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2faa9938-925f-40ee-869a-8485e17b09cd-image.png\" style=\"width: 362px; height: 132px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f050d57a-e0e1-4f4f-ad39-0053d184d0af-image.png\" style=\"width: 869px; height: 323px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27683,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["​<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ed57dd2d-d997-4c61-aa49-a75d99cf77f7-image.png\" style=\"width: 128px; height: 220px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fc62bb74-aa4b-4f6d-99cf-6475eca20a62-image.png\" style=\"width: 178px; height: 127px;\" />​","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fa79ef7b-21fa-4db1-a39f-de21689f762d-image.png\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 159px;\" />​","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66d7dcde-1929-498f-8254-8038ba2dd764-image.png\" style=\"width: 183px; height: 142px;\" />​"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<img height=\"138\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/11cd197a-69fa-47ca-8a3a-5a42213a905a-image.png\" width=\"210\" /></p>Compound (A)&nbsp;gives a white precipitate when warmed with alcoholic <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>means it contain a removable chloride&nbsp;atom(Benzylic position)<sub>.</sub>&nbsp;Oxidation of (A) gives an acid (B), <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>. (B) easily forms anhydride on heating. Means both acid should be ortho position of each other.<p><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f739a781-ac88-4863-8eac-590d7792d214-image.png\" style=\"width: 613px; height: 305px;\" /><br />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27678,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>CNCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NCCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CNCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NCCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Acidic character <math><mi>&#945;</mi></math> stability of conjugate base (anion)<br /><br />Stability of anion <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math><br /><br />Hence greater the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> effect greater will be the acidity<br /><br />Order of -I-effect <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>CN</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math> Hence, order of acidity &nbsp;will be<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>NC</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>COOH</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27659,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a7930ea2-f814-4b77-803f-4abce551f69b-image.png\" style=\"width: 59px; height: 71px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f582ffd8-fea7-4e42-8816-8030a8026161-image.png\" style=\"width: 49px; height: 73px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81621cd7-fc1a-48f6-895a-1ceb8f175d8a-image.png\" style=\"width: 103px; height: 72px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40074224-16d2-4840-b2b1-b082932ef1df-image.png\" style=\"width: 82px; height: 71px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/018500cf-7770-4785-9200-fbc75c9b983e-74c6beee-d093-4df9-8aa0-478e921005b2-image.png\" style=\"width: 319px; height: 147px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27686,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["benzophenone","acetophenone","benzoic acid","benzyl alcohol"],"answer":2,"solution":"Any aliphatic carbon with hydrogen attached to it, in combination with benzene ring, will be oxidized to benzoic acid by $\\mathrm{KMnO}_4 / \\mathrm{H}^{+}$.\nHence, (C) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":27645,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["alkylated product with ortho and para&nbsp;substitution.","secondary amine after acidic treatment.","an amide product.","positively charged nitrogen at benzene ring."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Aniline does not undergo Friedel-crafts reaction&nbsp;due to salt formation with aluminium chloride, the Lewis acid, which is used as a catalyst, whereas&nbsp;aniline is a strong base. So, an acid-base reaction will take place. Thus, aniline reacts with <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> to form a salt.<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/75d7b7ac-4e45-493a-91c6-85fa0ddc3273-9711822.png\" style=\"width: 270px; height: 157px;\" /><br />Due to the positive charge on the nitrogen atom (shows <math><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> effect and it is meta directing), electrophilic substitution in the benzene ring is deactivated. Hence, the Friedel-Crafts reaction will not take place in aniline.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27626,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A and D only","A,B and E only","B,C and E only","B and E only"],"answer":3,"solution":"(A) $\\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{C} \\equiv \\mathrm{N} \\xrightarrow[\\text { mild condition }]{\\text { (i) } \\mathrm{H}^{+} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}} \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{CONH}_2$<br />Under mild condition amide is formed because this reaction is typically slow if further more heat will supplied then it gets convert in to -COOH.<br />(B) $\\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{MgX} \\xrightarrow[\\text { (ii) } \\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}]{\\text {(i) } \\mathrm{CO}_2} \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{COOH}$<br />(C) $\\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{C} \\equiv \\mathrm{N} \\xrightarrow[\\text { (ii) } \\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}]{\\text {(i) } \\mathrm{SnCl}_2 / \\mathrm{HCl}} \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{CHO}$<br />(D) $\\mathrm{R} \\cdot \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\cdot \\mathrm{OH} \\xrightarrow{\\mathrm{PCC}} \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{CHO}$<br />(E) <br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/TBqlwFTjkSIABCdcP63HxkIiWKpYn9w9mCCbj3TBRoU.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27663,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eeed523f-8ce7-4824-922a-eacc9a8c74c2-image.png\" style=\"width: 112px; height: 186px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2a166754-69a5-4828-885a-a4c08db852ef-image.png\" style=\"width: 147px; height: 156px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5d478922-fda9-4181-a1cd-ffff32e4ece3-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0fbe9d4c-9cfd-4267-a16f-cf1e5e45d785-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 145px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Isomer&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi></math>&nbsp;on heating with sodalime gives toluene,hence it is an acid.Moreover since it has&nbsp;Degree of unsaturation 5 therefore it is an aromatic carboxylic acid.Since Carboxylic acid on heating gives toluene&nbsp;,therefore it is having&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group attached to the benzene ring.</p><p>Now it forms single isomer on halogenation, therefore&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group must be attached at para position with respect to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>COOH</mi></math>&nbsp;group.</p><p>Hence correct option is 1.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/394bbbfd-ceb6-44ca-a213-2335be70abcb-image.png\" style=\"width: 316px; height: 300px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27640,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When salicylic acid is heated with methyl alcohol, the carboxyl group of salicylic acid is esterified producing a strong-smelling liquid ester (methyl salicylate). Aspirin is prepared by chemical synthesis from salicylic acid, through acetylation with acetic anhydride.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/671e3d54-d3fa-47ae-8761-34b1efb27a37-9896850_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 602px; height: 150px;\" />&nbsp;Hence, reagent&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></math>&nbsp;respectively are:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27623,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["benzoic acid","benzoic acid and aniline","benzoic acid and chlorobenzene","chlorobenzene and aniline"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Xx9UZ-Pv7pMWFBCU1sEMG6ijlYWr71Yyh26ds--l7gs.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />Organic layer in funnel are mixture of chloro benzene and aniline","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27691,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["Phenol","Benzoic acid","Butanal","Benzaldehyde"],"answer":3,"solution":"Benzaldehyde does not contain $\\alpha$ - hydrogen. Hence goes for cannizarro's reaction forming alcohol and acid","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27692,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}-\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CHO}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{COOH}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{LiAl}^{\\mathrm{H}}{ }_4$ can reduce $\\mathrm{COOH}$ group and not the double bond\n$\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}-\\mathrm{COOH} \\underset{\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}-\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}}{\\stackrel{\\mathrm{LAH}}{\\longrightarrow}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":27693,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["propanoic acid and ammonium salt","ethanoic acid and ammonium salt","methylamine salt and ethanoic acid","ethylamine salt and methanoic acid"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{~N} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}+\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O} \\stackrel{\\mathrm{H}^{+}}{\\longrightarrow} \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{NH}_2+\\mathrm{HCOOH}$. Therefore it gives only one mono chloroalkane.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":27682,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["Etard reaction","Wolff-Kischner reaction","Rosenmund reaction","Hell-volhard-zelinsky reaction"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>This reaction is known as HVZ reaction.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4f9b8036-e7ee-4751-b47e-433fb887c796-image.png\" style=\"width: 522px; height: 102px;\" /></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, &quot;sans serif&quot;;\">Treatment with bromine and a catalytic amount of phosphorus leads to the selective <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>-</mo></math>bromination of carboxylic acids.</span></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27634,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VjkrPrIgtozA4MbQd_k2KjhibBgpg2COz7IZkPG_aSI.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/-BAD5FlBV4Y--QFY8kMmbgIsqJ1Kb3y5DZGMdQLt7NA.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Ke0MQM_9AAxezfrFRL7cBtUny2DMdAjLzyZ2JnDxnnQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\pi$ bonds $=4$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27627,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["\\(r  \\gt  q  \\gt  p  \\gt  s\\)","\\(q  \\gt  p  \\gt  r  \\gt  s\\)","\\(p  \\gt  r  \\gt  q  \\gt  s\\)","\\(p  \\gt  q  \\gt  r  \\gt  s\\)"],"answer":3,"solution":"Rate of hydrolysis \\(\\propto\\) Leaving group ability<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1fmgXuI01qyQTleHhIzYYCAOUoLmDcmqd4xTgttT1pY.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27637,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/825774a3-db3d-45a2-bdb3-1becacb9bd9b.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 94px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/59870980-f498-4bd3-8da1-9138418bff01.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 86px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/90d39f45-43b2-4fe8-aee3-78d4e6e75e56.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 97px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d1a666b5-51ee-4ea3-973d-908ae709c475.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 79px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SOCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is a halogenating agent. The carboxylic acid group of reactant changes to acid chloride. The acid chloride formed reacts with primary amine to give secondary amide. The secondary amide undergo reduction with lithium aluminium hydride to give secondary amine.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5546dec6-cec8-48ad-a320-e802a2d65c26.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 196px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27671,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math> convert ester into alcohol by reduction, it does not reduce <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></math> bond between carbon atoms.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/357f8ad0-6dc7-4e2a-b979-7f3cabea8072-image.png\" style=\"width: 804px; height: 90px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27676,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>IV</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"The rate of hydrolysis will depend on how likely a molecule is to accepting &nbsp;<math><mi>O</mi><msup><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp; ions. Rate of hydrolysis&nbsp;<math><mi>α</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>M</mi></math>&nbsp; effect or <math><mo>-</mo><mi>I</mi></math> of ester.&nbsp;<math><mo>-</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>I</mi></math>. <math><mo>-</mo><mi>N</mi><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp; is a strong <math><mi>E</mi><mi>W</mi><mi>G</mi></math> (Electron withdrawing group),<math><mo>-</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi></math> is a weak <math><mi>E</mi><mi>W</mi><mi>G</mi></math> and <math><mi>O</mi><mi>C</mi><msub><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> is an <math><mi>E</mi><mi>D</mi><mi>G</mi></math>(Electron donating group).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27690,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOC}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5+\\mathrm{NaCl}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{Cl}+\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{COONa}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCl}+\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{OH}+\\mathrm{NaOH}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COONa}+\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{OH}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27673,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/00kGSxKaFOpGgf9v_g65Oy9JdIoKOoPA4fzH96eFoAY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lUJF9OOv18EqWn5Mcac2FcZCpOGK5yepZHVkZfTrTzA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rTlVfWG62LyH8IxBnHBhH5XOij3bi5ZLKnwad6b7vIQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/XVAigqCcOXIABJyTp_E_qIwUm0URkSB5m-wnKLKm7Rk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eTSGo49aRK-_kmIdm94okiFJcdaZCnoQLOO3k9hoIQo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27672,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In the mentioned structures&nbsp;<math><msup><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> will get added to the carbon having slight positive charge.<br /><br />Presence of <math><mtext>C</mtext><mtext>l</mtext></math> increases the positive charge whereas an electron donating group like <math><mtext>N</mtext><msub><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> decreases the tendency.<br /><br />Rate of reaction <math><mo>&#8733;</mo></math> <math><mo>-</mo><mtext>M</mtext></math> or <math><mo>-</mo><mtext>I</mtext></math> group<br /><br />Rate of reaction <math><mo>&#8733;</mo></math> <math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mtext>M</mtext></mrow></mfrac></math> and <math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mtext>I</mtext></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br />Hence, the correct order will be:<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b5c0226c-a62e-42a7-8d33-561f2092b726-image.png\" style=\"width: 565px; height: 141px;\" /></p><p><img height=\"142\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e8c61ef6-c2c1-4121-8e4b-9a055c04bd3f-image.png\" width=\"450\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27622,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$A>D>B>C$","$C>A>D>B$","$C>B>A>D$","$A>D>C>B$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Product [A]: From PhNH₂, steps (1) NaNO₂ + HCl forms diazonium salt, (2) CuCN gives benzonitrile, (3) H₃O⁺/Δ hydrolyzes to benzoic acid (PhCOOH), pKa ≈ 4.2.<br>Product [B]: From CH₃CH₂CHO, Tollens' oxidation with $[Ag(NH_3)_2]^+$ produces acetic acid (CH₃COOH), pKa ≈ 4.8.<br>Product [C]: From CH₄ + O₂ with heat and Na₂Cr₂O₇/H⁺ produces formic acid (HCOOH), pKa ≈ 3.8 (strongest acid).<br>Product [D]: From PhCH₂MgBr + CO₂, the Grignard reaction produces phenylacetic acid (PhCH₂COOH), pKa ≈ 4.3.<br>Acidic strength order (lower pKa = stronger): C (3.8) > A (4.2) > D (4.3) > B (4.8).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27654,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Mg</mi><mo>/</mo></math> ether, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>NaCN</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>NaCN</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Mg</mi><mo>/</mo></math> ether, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8ac36412-d6ae-4eb3-8076-233700d34232-image.png\" style=\"width: 1106px; height: 170px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null}]